{{AFC submission|||ts=20120110192019|u=Mojorisin42|ns=5}}

'''Iris Bohnet''', a [[Swiss people|Swiss]] academic, is  Academic Dean and Professor of Public Policy at the  [[John F. Kennedy School of Government|Harvard Kennedy School]] in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]].<ref name="title">{{cite news|url=http://www.webcitation.org/64amVNAIr|title= Harvard Kennedy School: Academic Dean's Office|newspaper=Harvard Kennedy School website|date=|accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref> She is also the director of the Women and Public Policy Program,<ref name="wappp">{{cite news|url=http://www.webcitation.org/64an2JCHQ|title= Harvard Kennedy School Women and Public Policy Program: About|newspaper=Harvard Kennedy School website|date=|accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref> an associate director of the  Harvard Decision Science Laboratory,<ref name="hdsl">{{cite news|url=http://www.freezepage.com/1326217015CQWDSXWETU|title= Harvard Decision Science Labratory at Harvard Kennedy School: Faculty|newspaper=Harvard Decision Science Labratory website|date=|accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref> vice-chair of the  Program on Negotiation,<ref name="pon">{{cite news|url=http://www.webcitation.org/64anVVME7|title= Program on Negotiation at Harvard Law School: Faculty|newspaper=Program on Negotiation at Harvard Law School website|date=|accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref> and the faculty chair of the executive program  <U+201C>Global Leadership and Public Policy for the 21st Century<U+201D> for the [[World Economic Forum|World Economic Forum<U+2019>s]] [[List of Young Global Leaders|Young Global Leaders]].<ref name="hksee">{{cite news|url=http://www.webcitation.org/64anoXoay|title= Harvard Kennedy School Executive Education: Faculty|newspaper=Harvard Kennedy School Executive Education website|date=|accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref> She serves on the boards of the [[Geneva]]-based [[Graduate Institute of International and Development Studies]],<ref name="geneva">{{cite news|url=http://www.webcitation.org/64aoEFCkU|title= The Graduate Institute, Geneva: The Foundation Board|newspaper=The Graduate Institute, Geneva website|date=|accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref> the [[Vienna University of Economics and Business]]<ref name="vienna">{{cite news|url=http://www.webcitation.org/64aoeAXdb|title= Vienna University of Economics and Business: Wissenschaftlicher Beirat|newspaper=Vienna University of Economics and Business website|date=|accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref> and numerous academic journals. Additionally, she is a member of the Global Agenda Council on Women<U+2019>s Empowerment of the World Economic Forum.<ref name="gac">{{cite news|url=http://www.webcitation.org/64apQaqqw|title= Global Agenda Council on Womens Empowerment 2011: Members|newspaper=World Economic Forum website|date=|accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref>

Dr. Bohnet teaches decision-making, negotiation and gender in public policy and leadership in both degree and executive programs, and has been engaged in the teaching, training and consulting of private and public sector leaders in the United States, Europe, India and the Middle East.<ref name="bio">{{cite news|url=http://www.freezepage.com/1326219766NHLJUBEFIU|title= Harvard Kennedy School: Iris Bohnet|newspaper=Harvard Kennedy School website|date=|accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref>

A behavioral economist combining insights from economics and psychology, her research focuses on questions of trust and decision-making, often with a gender or cross-cultural perspective.<ref name="bio" /> Her most recent research examines <U+201C>gender equality nudges,<U+201D> which are described as "interventions that decrease the gender gaps in organizations, politics and society."<ref name="bio" /> Dr. Bohnet<U+2019>s academic work has been published in the top peer-reviewed journals of her profession, including ''[[The American Economic Review]]'', ''[[American Political Science Review]]'', ''Experimental Economics'', and ''[[Quarterly Journal of Economics|The Quarterly Journal of Economics]]''.<ref name="bio" /> Her work has been profiled by media outlets around the world, including ''Bilanz'', ''[[Bloomberg|Bloomberg News]]'', ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', ''[[The Economist]]'', ''[[Emirates Business 24/7|Emirates Business]]'', ''[[Financial Times]]'', ''[[Forbes]]'', ''[[Handelsblatt]]'', ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', ''[[Neue Z<U+00FC>rcher Zeitung]]'', ''[[Tages-Anzeiger]]'', ''Swiss Television'', and ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''.<ref name="bio" />

A native of Switzerland, she received her Ph.D. in Economics from the [[University of Zurich]] in 1997 and spent a year as a research fellow at the [[Haas School of Business]] at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] from 1997-1998.<ref name="bio" /> She joined the Harvard Kennedy School as an assistant professor in 1998 and was made full professor in 2006.<ref name="bio" />


